{"parse":{"title":"Xochitl (Toltec)","pageid":35378338,"revid":845241574,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"fn\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color: #cbe; font-size: 125%\">Xochitl</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<i>Empress of the Toltecs</i> <small></small></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" class=\"photo\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"El descubrimiento del pulque Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Obreg\u00f3n.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg/220px-El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"195\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg/330px-El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg/440px-El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"5000\" data-file-height=\"4437\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Reign</th><td>\n877-916</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Predecessor</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Tecpancaltzin_Iztaccaltzin\" title=\"Tecpancaltzin Iztaccaltzin\">Tecpancaltzin Iztaccaltzin</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Successor</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Ce_Acatl_Topiltzin\" title=\"Ce Acatl Topiltzin\">C\u0113 \u0100catl Topiltzin QuetzalCoatl</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\nBefore 877<br /><a href=\"/wiki/Toltec_Empire\" title=\"Toltec Empire\">Toltec Empire</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>\n916<br /><a href=\"/wiki/Toltec_Empire\" title=\"Toltec Empire\">Toltec Empire</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Father</th><td>\nPapantzin</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Mother</th><td>\nUnknown</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Religion</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Mesoamerican_religion\" title=\"Mesoamerican religion\">Toltec religion</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Xochitl</b> (r. 877-916) was a <a href=\"/wiki/Toltec\" title=\"Toltec\">Toltec</a> Queen and wife of <a href=\"/wiki/Tecpancaltzin_Iztaccaltzin\" title=\"Tecpancaltzin Iztaccaltzin\">Tecpancaltzin Iztaccaltzin</a>. Her existence beyond legend is questionable, and accounts of her life are mainly based on the writings of indigenous historian <a href=\"/wiki/Fernando_de_Alva_Ixtlilxochitl\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Fernando de Alva Ixtlilxochitl\">Fernando de Alva Ixtlilxochitl</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Biography\">Biography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Xochitl_(Toltec)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Biography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Xochitl was a mistress of the Toltec Emperor Tecpancaltzin, bearing him a son. (Tecpancaltzin had only daughters by his first wife, Maxio). After Maxio died, Xochitl became recognized as queen.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Her son became heir and was known as Topiltzin-<a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Meconetzin&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Meconetzin (page does not exist)\">Meconetzin</a>.\n</p><p>When she was elderly, civil war erupted in the <a href=\"/wiki/Toltec_Empire\" title=\"Toltec Empire\">Toltec Empire</a>. Xochitl called upon other women to join her in battle, and created and led a battalion made entirely of women soldiers. She died on the battlefield.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The son of Xochitl and Tecpancaltzin, <a href=\"/wiki/Topiltzin_Ce_Acatl_Quetzalcoatl\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Topiltzin Ce Acatl Quetzalcoatl\">Topiltzin</a>, was the last of the Toltec kings, before he was overthrown in the civil war. It was during the final stand of the Toltecs at <a href=\"/wiki/Tultitlan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Tultitlan\">Tultitlan</a> that Tecpancaltzin and Xochitl were slain in battle.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Depiction_in_art\">Depiction in art</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Xochitl_(Toltec)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Depiction in art\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg/220px-El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"195\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg/330px-El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg/440px-El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"5000\" data-file-height=\"4437\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:El_descubrimiento_del_pulque_Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Obreg%C3%B3n.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>El descubrimiento del pulque</i> by Jos\u00e9 Obreg\u00f3n</div></div></div>\n<p>A well-known painting of Xochitl and Tecpancaltzin, <i>El descubrimiento del pulque</i>, was completed in 1869 by Mexican artist <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Jos%C3%A9_Obreg%C3%B3n&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Jos\u00e9 Obreg\u00f3n (page does not exist)\">Jos\u00e9 Obreg\u00f3n</a>.  Obreg\u00f3n was trained, and painted in, a classical style popular in the 19th century. <i>El descubrimiento del pulque</i> is based on historian <a href=\"/wiki/Fernando_de_Alva_Ixtlilxochitl\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Fernando de Alva Ixtlilxochitl\">Fernando de Alva Ixtlilxochitl</a>'s description of Xochitl as a beautiful virgin brought to Tecpancaltzin by her father, Papatzin. Papatzin was a Toltec noble, and a cultivator of maguey plants, also called <a href=\"/wiki/Agave\" title=\"Agave\">agave</a> plants and related to aloe. Xochitl presented to Tecpancaltzin a drink that she and/or her father invented, <a href=\"/wiki/Pulque\" title=\"Pulque\">pulque</a>, made from the honey of maguey. The painting was part of a cultural rise in Mexican nationalism during the period, yet the influence of classical European art symbolism appears throughout the painting. Xochitl is depicted as a Greek princess, and Tecpancaltzin is shown as a \"Hellenic Apollo\"; Mexico's \"Indian past was thus civilized through a classical romantic filter\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>More recently, Xochitl appears as one of the 999 women included in American artist <a href=\"/wiki/Judy_Chicago\" title=\"Judy Chicago\">Judy Chicago</a>'s installation work, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Dinner_Party\" title=\"The Dinner Party\">The Dinner Party</a></i>. Xochitl is named in the <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_women_in_the_Heritage_Floor\" title=\"List of women in the Heritage Floor\">Heritage Floor</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Xochitl_(Toltec)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Bancroft, Hubert Howe (2009) [1883]. <i>The native races [of the Pacific states]</i> (University of California ed.). A. L. Bancroft &amp; company. p.&#160;270.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+native+races+%5Bof+the+Pacific+states%5D&amp;rft.pages=270&amp;rft.edition=University+of+California&amp;rft.pub=A.+L.+Bancroft+%26+company&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.aulast=Bancroft&amp;rft.aufirst=Hubert+Howe&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AXochitl+%28Toltec%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Salas, Elizabeth (1990). <i>Soldaderas in the Mexican Military: Myth and History</i>. University of Texas Press. p.&#160;3. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780292776388\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780292776388\">9780292776388</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Soldaderas+in+the+Mexican+Military%3A+Myth+and+History&amp;rft.pages=3&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Texas+Press&amp;rft.date=1990&amp;rft.isbn=9780292776388&amp;rft.aulast=Salas&amp;rft.auf